      summary:
          'India launches its first comprehensive Carbon Credit Trading Scheme (CCTS) regulated by the Bureau of Energy Efficiency to meet Paris Agreement targets.',
      content:
          'The Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change has launched India\'s first comprehensive Carbon Credit Trading Scheme (CCTS), establishing a market-based mechanism for industries to trade carbon credits and reduce greenhouse gas emissions.\n\nHow the Scheme Works:\n1. The government sets emission intensity benchmarks for obligated industries\n2. Industries performing better than benchmarks earn Carbon Credit Certificates (CCCs)\n3. Industries unable to meet targets must purchase CCCs from the market\n4. The trading creates a financial incentive for cleaner production\n\nInstitutional Framework:\n• Bureau of Energy Efficiency (BEE): Designated as the administrator\n• Indian Carbon Market (ICM): The trading platform\n• The Grid Controller of India: Provides emission data from the power sector\n• Central Electricity Regulatory Commission (CERC): Approves market procedures\n\nIndia\'s Climate Targets:\nThe scheme aligns with India\'s updated Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs) under the Paris Agreement:\n- 45% reduction in emission intensity of GDP by 2030 (from 2005 levels)\n- 50% cumulative electric power from non-fossil fuel-based energy resources by 2030\n- Net-zero emissions by 2070\n\nGlobal Context:\nIndia\'s carbon market follows the model of the EU Emissions Trading System (EU ETS), which has been operational since 2005. China launched its national carbon market in 2021.',
