      content:
          'The 22nd Law Commission of India has initiated a fresh examination of the Uniform Civil Code (UCC) by inviting public and stakeholder consultations. The issue has been a longstanding constitutional and political debate in India.\n\nConstitutional Context:\n• Article 44 under Directive Principles of State Policy (Part IV) states: "The State shall endeavour to secure for the citizens a uniform civil code throughout the territory of India."\n• Personal laws currently govern matters of marriage, divorce, inheritance, adoption, and maintenance separately for different religious communities.\n\nCurrent Personal Law Framework:\n1. Hindu Personal Law: Hindu Marriage Act (1955), Hindu Succession Act (1956), Hindu Adoption Act (1956)\n2. Muslim Personal Law: Muslim Personal Law (Shariat) Application Act (1937), Dissolution of Muslim Marriages Act (1939)\n3. Christian Personal Law: Indian Christian Marriage Act (1872), Indian Divorce Act (1869)\n4. Parsi Personal Law: Parsi Marriage and Divorce Act (1936)\n5. Special Marriage Act (1954): Available to all citizens irrespective of religion\n\nLandmark Judgments:\n- Shah Bano Case (1985): SC upheld Muslim woman\'s right to maintenance under CrPC\n- Sarla Mudgal (1995): SC urged implementation of UCC\n- Shayara Bano (2017): SC declared Triple Talaq unconstitutional\n- Goa Model: Goa has a Common Civil Code based on Portuguese Civil Code — the only state with a UCC\n\nArguments For: Gender justice, national integration, simplification of law, constitutional directive\nArguments Against: Religious freedom (Articles 25-28), cultural diversity, minority rights, federal concerns',
