              'The Indus Valley Civilization (c. 3300–1300 BCE), also known as the Harappan Civilization, was one of the three earliest urban civilizations of the world, alongside Mesopotamia and Egypt.\n\n**Key Sites & Discoveries:**\n• **Harappa** (Punjab, Pakistan) — First discovered site; granaries, workers\' quarters\n• **Mohenjo-daro** (Sindh, Pakistan) — Great Bath, Great Granary, Bronze Dancing Girl, Priest King\n• **Dholavira** (Gujarat, India) — UNESCO World Heritage Site; unique water management system; signboard with Indus script\n• **Lothal** (Gujarat, India) — Ancient dockyard, bead-making factory, fire altars suggesting ritualistic practices\n• **Kalibangan** (Rajasthan, India) — Evidence of earliest ploughed field; fire altars\n• **Rakhigarhi** (Haryana, India) — Largest IVC site in India; ongoing DNA analysis providing insights into population genetics\n\n**Key Features:**\n- Urban planning with grid-pattern streets and advanced drainage systems\n- Standardized weights and measures using binary and decimal systems\n- Script remains undeciphered — longest inscription has only 17 characters\n- Economy based on agriculture (wheat, barley, cotton) and long-distance trade with Mesopotamia\n- No evidence of temples or large palaces — suggesting a relatively egalitarian society\n- Declined around 1800 BCE — possible causes include climate change, river drying, and floods\n\n**UPSC Relevance:** Frequently asked in Prelims and Mains. Important for Art & Culture paper too.',
