          content:
              'India can be divided into six major physiographic divisions:\n\n**1. The Northern Mountains (Himalayas)**\n• Three parallel ranges: Greater Himalayas (Himadri), Lesser Himalayas (Himachal), Outer Himalayas (Shivaliks)\n• Highest peak: K2 (8,611m) in PoK; within India: Kanchenjunga (8,586m)\n• Young fold mountains — still rising due to tectonic activity\n• Source of major rivers: Ganga, Yamuna, Brahmaputra\n\n**2. The Northern Plains (Indo-Gangetic Plain)**\n• Alluvial deposits from Himalayan rivers\n• Sub-divisions: Bhabar (pebble zone), Terai (marshy), Bhangar (older alluvium), Khadar (newer alluvium)\n• Most fertile region — India\'s food bowl\n• Major rivers: Indus, Ganga, Brahmaputra systems\n\n**3. The Peninsular Plateau**\n• Oldest landmass — part of Gondwana land\n• Two sub-divisions: Central Highlands (north of Narmada) and Deccan Plateau (south of Narmada)\n• Rich in mineral resources: iron ore, coal, manganese, bauxite\n\n**4. The Indian Desert (Thar)**\n• Located in western Rajasthan\n• Arid climate with less than 150mm annual rainfall\n• Luni is the only significant river (flows into Rann of Kutch)\n• Indira Gandhi Canal: Brings water from Sutlej-Beas to Thar\n\n**5. The Coastal Plains**\n• Western Coastal Plain: Konkan (Maharashtra), Malabar (Kerala) — narrow and steep\n• Eastern Coastal Plain: Coromandel (TN), Northern Circars — wider and suitable for agriculture\n• Major lagoons: Chilika Lake (Odisha), Vembanad Lake (Kerala)\n\n**6. The Islands**\n• Andaman & Nicobar: 572 islands in Bay of Bengal; India\'s only active volcano (Barren Island)\n• Lakshadweep: 36 coral islands in Arabian Sea; smallest UT of India',
