              '**Monsoon Mechanism:**\nIndia\'s climate is dominated by the monsoon system, characterized by seasonal reversal of winds.\n\n**Southwest Monsoon (June–September):**\n• Primary source of India\'s rainfall (~75% of annual rainfall)\n• Two branches: Arabian Sea Branch and Bay of Bengal Branch\n• Arabian Sea branch hits Western Ghats first — causes heavy rainfall on windward side\n• Bay of Bengal branch enters NE India — Cherrapunji/Mawsynram receive world\'s highest rainfall\n• Onset: Kerala by June 1 (±7 days), reaches entire India by mid-July\n• Withdrawal: September from NW India, October from southern India\n\n**Northeast Monsoon (October–December):**\n• Retreating monsoon brings rainfall to Tamil Nadu and Andhra Pradesh\n• Tamil Nadu receives more rain during NE monsoon than SW monsoon\n• Cyclonic activity in Bay of Bengal during this period\n\n**Important Concepts:**\n• ITCZ (Inter-Tropical Convergence Zone): Low-pressure belt that shifts with seasons\n• El Niño: Warming of Pacific Ocean — causes weak monsoon (drought conditions)\n• La Niña: Cooling of Pacific Ocean — causes strong monsoon (flood risk)\n• Indian Ocean Dipole (IOD): Temperature difference between western and eastern Indian Ocean\n• Jet Streams: Upper-level winds that influence monsoon onset and withdrawal',
