              'Fundamental Rights are enshrined in Part III of the Indian Constitution, inspired by the US Bill of Rights.\n\n**Six Fundamental Rights:**\n\n1. **Right to Equality (Art. 14–18)**\n   - Art. 14: Equality before law & equal protection of laws\n   - Art. 15: Prohibition of discrimination on grounds of religion, race, caste, sex, place of birth\n   - Art. 16: Equality of opportunity in public employment\n   - Art. 17: Abolition of Untouchability\n   - Art. 18: Abolition of Titles (except military and academic)\n\n2. **Right to Freedom (Art. 19–22)**\n   - Art. 19: Six freedoms — speech, assembly, association, movement, residence, profession\n   - Art. 20: Protection against ex-post facto laws, double jeopardy, self-incrimination\n   - Art. 21: Right to Life and Personal Liberty (includes Right to Privacy, Right to Education)\n   - Art. 21A: Right to Education (6–14 years) — added by 86th Amendment, 2002\n   - Art. 22: Protection against arbitrary arrest and detention\n\n3. **Right against Exploitation (Art. 23–24)**\n   - Art. 23: Prohibition of human trafficking and forced labor (begar)\n   - Art. 24: Prohibition of child labor in factories, mines, and hazardous occupations (below 14 years)\n\n4. **Right to Freedom of Religion (Art. 25–28)**\n   - Freedom of conscience, practice, profess, propagate religion\n   - Subject to public order, morality, and health\n\n5. **Cultural and Educational Rights (Art. 29–30)**\n   - Protection of interests of minorities\n   - Right to establish and administer educational institutions\n\n6. **Right to Constitutional Remedies (Art. 32)**\n   - Dr. Ambedkar called it the "Heart and Soul" of the Constitution\n   - Five writs: Habeas Corpus, Mandamus, Prohibition, Certiorari, Quo Warranto\n\n**Note:** Right to Property was removed from Fundamental Rights by the 44th Amendment Act, 1978. It is now a legal right under Article 300A.',
