          content:
              'The Reserve Bank of India (est. 1935, HQ: Mumbai) uses various instruments to control money supply, credit, and interest rates in the economy.\n\n**Quantitative (General) Tools:**\n\n1. **Repo Rate**: Rate at which RBI lends overnight to commercial banks against government securities\n   - Current: 6.25% (as of latest MPC review)\n   - Increase → Money becomes expensive → Controls inflation\n   - Decrease → Money becomes cheaper → Boosts economic growth\n\n2. **Standing Deposit Facility (SDF) Rate**: Rate at which RBI absorbs excess liquidity without collateral\n   - Replaced Reverse Repo Rate as the floor of the LAF corridor\n\n3. **Marginal Standing Facility (MSF) Rate**: Rate at which banks can borrow overnight from RBI in emergencies\n   - Usually Repo Rate + 25 bps\n\n4. **Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR)**: % of deposits banks must keep with RBI as cash\n   - Banks earn NO interest on CRR deposits\n   - Current: 4.5%\n\n5. **Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR)**: % of deposits banks must invest in government securities, gold, etc.\n   - Current: 18%\n\n6. **Open Market Operations (OMO)**: RBI buys/sells government securities in open market\n   - Buy → Injects liquidity → Increases money supply\n   - Sell → Absorbs liquidity → Decreases money supply\n\n**Qualitative (Selective) Tools:**\n- Margin Requirements\n- Moral Suasion (persuasion through appeals)\n- Selective Credit Controls\n- Direct Action\n\n**Monetary Policy Framework:**\n- Inflation targeting framework adopted in 2016\n- Target: 4% CPI inflation with ±2% band (2%–6%)\n- MPC decides monetary policy every 2 months (6 meetings/year)',
