          content:
              '**Union Budget (Article 112):**\nThe Annual Financial Statement presented by the Finance Minister in Parliament, showing estimated receipts and expenditure for the coming financial year (April–March).\n\n**Key Fiscal Indicators:**\n\n1. **Revenue Deficit** = Revenue Expenditure – Revenue Receipts\n   - Shows how much of revenue expenditure is financed by borrowing\n\n2. **Fiscal Deficit** = Total Expenditure – Total Receipts (excluding borrowings)\n   - Indicates total borrowing requirement of the government\n   - FRBM Act targets: Below 3% of GDP\n\n3. **Primary Deficit** = Fiscal Deficit – Interest Payments\n   - Shows the borrowing requirement excluding interest obligations\n\n4. **Effective Revenue Deficit** = Revenue Deficit – Grants for creation of capital assets\n   - Introduced by 15th Finance Commission\n\n**Types of Expenditure:**\n- Revenue Expenditure: Day-to-day expenses (salaries, interest payments, subsidies)\n- Capital Expenditure: Asset creation (infrastructure, machinery, loans given)\n\n**Revenue Sources:**\n- Tax Revenue: Direct taxes (income tax, corporate tax) + Indirect taxes (GST, customs)\n- Non-Tax Revenue: Dividends from PSUs, RBI surplus, fees, fines\n- Capital Receipts: Recovery of loans, disinvestment, borrowings\n\n**Important Bodies:**\n- Finance Commission (Art. 280): Recommends sharing of taxes between Centre and States\n- CAG (Art. 148): Audits government accounts\n- GST Council (Art. 279A): Decides GST rates and rules',
