              '**Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO):**\n- Founded: 1969; HQ: Bengaluru\n- Chairman reports to PM through Department of Space\n- Key launch centre: Satish Dhawan Space Centre, Sriharikota (SDSC SHAR)\n\n**Major Missions:**\n\n**Chandrayaan Series (Moon):**\n- Chandrayaan-1 (2008): India\'s first lunar mission; discovered water molecules on Moon\n- Chandrayaan-2 (2019): Orbiter successful; Vikram lander crash-landed\n- Chandrayaan-3 (2023): Successful soft landing on south pole; Pragyan rover detected sulphur\n\n**Aditya-L1 (2023):** India\'s first solar observatory; placed at Sun-Earth L1 point\n\n**Mars Orbiter Mission/Mangalyaan (2013):**\n- India\'s first interplanetary mission\n- India became 1st Asian country to reach Mars orbit\n- Most cost-effective Mars mission: Rs 450 crore (~\$74M)\n\n**Gaganyaan (Upcoming):**\n- India\'s first crewed spaceflight program\n- Will launch 3 Indian astronauts to LEO (400 km) for 3 days\n- Vyommitra: Half-humanoid robot for test flights\n\n**Launch Vehicles:**\n- **PSLV** (Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle): Workhorse; 50+ missions; launched Chandrayaan-1, MOM, Aditya-L1\n- **LVM3** (Launch Vehicle Mark-3, formerly GSLV Mk III): Heavy-lift; 4 tonnes to GTO; used for Chandrayaan-3\n- **SSLV** (Small Satellite Launch Vehicle): For small satellites (up to 500 kg to LEO)\n\n**Satellite Systems:**\n- NavIC (Navigation with Indian Constellation): India\'s GPS alternative; 7 satellites\n- GSAT series: Communication satellites\n- Cartosat/Resourcesat: Earth observation\n- IRNSS: Indian Regional Navigation Satellite System\n\n**Commercial Arm:**\nNewSpace India Limited (NSIL) and Antrix Corporation for commercial launches',
          pdfUrl: 'https://ncert.nic.in/textbook/pdf/keph108.pdf',
          lastUpdated: DateTime.now(),
        ),
        StudyNote(
          id: 's2',
          title: 'Emerging Technologies — AI, Blockchain, Quantum Computing',
          content:
              '**1. Artificial Intelligence (AI):**\n\n• Machine Learning (ML): Systems that learn from data without explicit programming\n• Deep Learning: Neural networks with many layers — basis of modern AI\n• Generative AI: ChatGPT, Bard — creates new content (text, images, code)\n• India\'s AI Strategy: IndiaAI Mission (Rs 10,372 crore) — focuses on compute capacity, foundational AI models, datasets, and AI applications\n• Ethical concerns: Bias, privacy, job displacement, deepfakes, misinformation\n\n**2. Blockchain Technology:**\n• Decentralized, immutable ledger of transactions secured by cryptography\n• Types: Public (Bitcoin), Private (Hyperledger), Consortium\n• Applications: CBDCs, supply chain tracking, land records, voting systems\n• India: RBI\'s e-Rupee (CBDC) uses a centralized version of blockchain principles\n\n**3. Quantum Computing:**\n• Uses quantum bits (qubits) that can be in superposition — both 0 and 1 simultaneously\n• Key principles: Superposition, Entanglement, Quantum Tunneling\n• India: National Quantum Mission (Rs 6,003 crore) — targets quantum computers with 50+ qubits by 2030\n• Applications: Drug discovery, cryptography, optimization, climate modeling\n\n**4. 5G & 6G Technology:**\n• 5G: Launched in India (Oct 2022); speeds up to 10 Gbps; ultra-low latency (1ms)\n• Enables IoT, smart cities, autonomous vehicles, telemedicine\n• 6G: Expected by 2030; will integrate AI natively into the network; terahertz frequencies\n• BharatNet: Optical fiber network connecting 6 lakh villages for digital connectivity\n\n**5. Cybersecurity:**\n• CERT-In (Indian Computer Emergency Response Team): National nodal agency\n• National Cyber Security Policy 2013\n• Cyber Surakshit Bharat initiative\n• Data Protection: Digital Personal Data Protection Act, 2023',
          lastUpdated: DateTime.now(),
        ),
      ],
    ),
